Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:24.470 --> 00:00:26.590
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Good
evening, welcome everyone.

00:00:26.590 --> 00:00:29.040
Nice to see some friendly
regular faces

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:31.200
and also some new folks
out here tonight.

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:34.310
My name is Nicholas Brown,
I am a music specialist

00:00:34.310 --> 00:00:36.120
and concert producer
here at the library.

00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:39.420
I'm very pleased to introduce
to you two wonderful colleagues.

00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:43.960
On my far left is Herve
Boutry who is director general

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:46.700
of Ensemble Intercontemporain
[foreign language].

00:00:46.700 --> 00:00:52.770
Yeah, I really have been
practicing it's kind of funny.

00:00:52.770 --> 00:00:57.600 position:56%
And to my immediate left is Matthias
Pintscher who is the music director

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:01.780
of Ensemble and also a
distinguished composer.

00:01:01.780 --> 00:01:04.870
We're very thrilled to have them
both here to share some thoughts

00:01:04.870 --> 00:01:07.640
with you this evening before
a super exciting concert,

00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:10.730
which is the Ensemble's DC debut.

00:01:10.730 --> 00:01:13.920
So let's kick it off.

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:19.010
Tell us a bit about your
impression of DC so far.

00:01:19.010 --> 00:01:22.580
No politics.

00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:26.020
&gt;&gt; Herve Boutry: Well we
arrived yesterday night

00:01:26.020 --> 00:01:33.700
and we enjoyed fantastic acoustic
of the [inaudible] auditorium.

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:37.500
And we are very happy
to be here because it's

00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:43.150
for us also the conclusion of a
wonderful tour through the US.

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:47.500
We started some days ago,
two weeks ago in Berkeley,

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:51.760
we had four days residency
there and four days

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:54.420
in Chapel Hill, North Carolina.

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:59.630
And these residences we have
interactive with the universities

00:01:59.630 --> 00:02:04.750 position:56%
and had a different focus on the
repertoire because it was of course,

00:02:04.750 --> 00:02:08.640
more contemporary on one side.

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:10.420
We have a very contemporary
program tonight.

00:02:10.420 --> 00:02:12.780
&gt;&gt; Matthias Pintscher: We
have so classical tonight yes.

00:02:12.780 --> 00:02:17.020
&gt;&gt; Herve Boutry: But tonight we
have also classical repertoire

00:02:17.020 --> 00:02:22.950
and so that's my first
impression or expression

00:02:22.950 --> 00:02:28.060
from Washington, DC up to now.

00:02:28.060 --> 00:02:33.790 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Matthias Pintscher: I mean, it's
obviously beautiful to see this city

00:02:33.790 --> 00:02:37.870
and I've been to DC many,
many times, but I think never

00:02:37.870 --> 00:02:41.410
at that time of the year where
you see the beautiful foliage

00:02:41.410 --> 00:02:44.740
of the leaves and we're very
fortunate with the weather

00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:48.600
and the sun, which is also kind
of irritating and confusing

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:50.390
because it is just not normal.

00:02:50.390 --> 00:02:53.930
And I don't really know
what you think of it.

00:02:53.930 --> 00:02:58.230
But I mean right now we just
walked over and I was going

00:02:58.230 --> 00:03:03.380
through some manuscripts
of Beethoven and Schoenberg

00:03:03.380 --> 00:03:07.010
and Copeland and we received
the news from what is going

00:03:07.010 --> 00:03:08.400
on in this very moment in Paris.

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:14.360
So it is emotionally very
how can I even put it,

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:18.320
I'm really moved and now.

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:23.390
But this is exactly what makes an
artist because now we may or have

00:03:23.390 --> 00:03:27.300
to play this concert with
all these emotions that go on

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:28.790
and it's the only thing we can do

00:03:28.790 --> 00:03:30.320
because we're not in
Paris right now.

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:34.860
So what we can do is just to keep
doing exactly what we believe in,

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:37.060
which is play the music
in the most painful way

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:39.900
so it brings people together.

00:03:39.900 --> 00:03:44.030
I I'm really emotional it's very
disturbing what is going on.

00:03:44.030 --> 00:03:45.330
&gt;&gt; Herve Boutry: You
have to explain.

00:03:45.330 --> 00:03:46.630
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown:
Yeah, I got the feels

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:49.980
that all you needed info,
so don't worry about it.

00:03:49.980 --> 00:03:52.410
There's been new within
the last couple of hours

00:03:52.410 --> 00:03:54.880
of a major series of
attacks in Paris.

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:59.390
And if you have people living in
Paris, please you want to check

00:03:59.390 --> 00:04:02.680
in with them as soon as you can
and it's not clear who or why

00:04:02.680 --> 00:04:04.640
or the extent or anything
like that yet.

00:04:04.640 --> 00:04:09.120
So it's -- tonight will
probably be a very difficult

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:14.290
and emotional evening for everyone
who's going to be on stage.

00:04:14.290 --> 00:04:16.590
So with that note.

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:22.340
With a program like this evening's

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:26.240
where there's some very highbrow
art music that is, you know,

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:27.900
the creme de la creme
in terms of repertoire

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:30.460
and then we have some
really great new repertoire.

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:37.150
What can we gain in terms of human
experience from this type of music,

00:04:37.150 --> 00:04:39.450
particularly tonight's program?

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:43.410
&gt;&gt; Matthias Pintscher: We
gain from it what we have

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:52.060
and it brings us directly to the
question that's being put out over

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:57.900
and over again like when
audience members ask me

00:04:57.900 --> 00:05:01.850
or someone what should we listen
for, can you tell us something

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:05.120
that helps us to be
guided through a piece.

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:09.260
And I said well you guide
yourself, you listen with your ears

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:13.200
and you listen with the
qualities that you have.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:18.410
I mean listening means to involve
yourself and with all great art

00:05:18.410 --> 00:05:25.250
and it could be visual, it could
be sonic you find something

00:05:25.250 --> 00:05:27.210
about yourself and it's not really,

00:05:27.210 --> 00:05:31.460
it's kind of the artist is
stepping back and hands it over.

00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:34.400
And think that is what makes
it very, very beautiful

00:05:34.400 --> 00:05:36.710
and music describes time.

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:41.640
So the one thing we
have to accept is

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:46.600
that someone else has defined
a certain span of time for us,

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:50.070
which nowadays seem to
becoming something that's almost

00:05:50.070 --> 00:05:53.590
uncomfortable because we are
so used to being in control

00:05:53.590 --> 00:05:56.650
of how we define the flow of time.

00:05:56.650 --> 00:06:00.400
We zap through something, we stop
something, we turn something off

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:04.980
and when you listen to sound

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:08.610
and music you can't do
that, you have to sit there.

00:06:08.610 --> 00:06:14.250
I mean you can walk out, but
you have to listen to 13 pieces,

00:06:14.250 --> 00:06:18.690
13 minutes or 25 minutes
or 70 minutes of music

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:22.170
that someone has designed
and conceived for you

00:06:22.170 --> 00:06:27.700
because he believes or she in
how that time is happening.

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:31.950
So it enables us to
completely let go

00:06:31.950 --> 00:06:33.950
and I think that's a
beautiful condition.

00:06:33.950 --> 00:06:36.490
And people sometimes
feel the opposite

00:06:36.490 --> 00:06:38.430
that they don't feel
qualified enough

00:06:38.430 --> 00:06:40.610
because they might not know enough,

00:06:40.610 --> 00:06:44.360
but every one is the most
qualified listener anyway,

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:46.350
there is no such thing
as a qualification.

00:06:46.350 --> 00:06:48.130
You can know more about music,

00:06:48.130 --> 00:06:51.080
but it doesn't help you
to understand music.

00:06:51.080 --> 00:06:59.470
So just listen and listen to
what you have and it's that easy.

00:06:59.470 --> 00:07:01.920
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Thank
you that was really great.

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:04.430
Maybe to switch back
to regular topics now

00:07:04.430 --> 00:07:07.220
because I guess we're going
to get pretty emotional here.

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:10.590
But Herve, could you tell us a
bit about how your relationship

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:14.080
and the Ensemble's relationship
began with Matthias and how

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:17.780
that grew into his current
role as music director.

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:21.080
&gt;&gt; Herve Boutry: I have been with
this Ensemble already 20 years

00:07:21.080 --> 00:07:29.220 position:56%
and I have been very close to Pierre
Boulez when he asked me to come.

00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:36.860 position:56%
And I must say it is what we live at
the moment is a very fortunate time

00:07:36.860 --> 00:07:44.030
because after so fantastic
years we are now getting

00:07:44.030 --> 00:07:49.720
like any organization you
have changes, evolution

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:55.200
and we have the impression now
that Pierre Boulez is no longer

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:58.120
in the condition to be
very present with us.

00:07:58.120 --> 00:08:03.510
He's of course, in in contact with
us, but not physically present.

00:08:03.510 --> 00:08:11.590 position:56%
And we have the impression to become
adult and not to be the children

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:15.430
of Pierre Boulez and this
has been enhanced very,

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:17.700
very strongly from the moment

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:25.260 position:56%
when Matthias Pintscher has been saw
sharing destiny because it happened

00:08:25.260 --> 00:08:28.860
like good food or we say in French.

00:08:28.860 --> 00:08:36.620
In 2011, we appointed him
on June 12 and he started

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:41.790
with the Ensemble in 2013.

00:08:41.790 --> 00:08:49.230
And I say that because it is not --
I want also to make a distinction

00:08:49.230 --> 00:08:54.410
between what an ensemble looks
like, we are not a small orchestra.

00:08:54.410 --> 00:09:01.450
We are a group of soloists,
a group of individuality,

00:09:01.450 --> 00:09:08.450
strong personalities and what is
very important in such a group is

00:09:08.450 --> 00:09:17.720
to be able to always ask yourself
why are you performing it together.

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:20.780
And when you have somebody
like Matthias,

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:25.120
when you have these personalities

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:29.410 position:56%
at this very moment I have the
impression you are on the right wave

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:35.080
to go very much further
in aesthetically,

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:39.210
musically in the artistic
experience.

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:43.730
That's my statement
now if you ask me

00:09:43.730 --> 00:09:48.010
about my relationship
with the Ensemble.

00:09:48.010 --> 00:09:51.690
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Is there a
noticeable change in the focus

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:55.240
of the Ensemble now
and moving forward

00:09:55.240 --> 00:10:01.610
versus in the past few
tenures of music directors?

00:10:01.610 --> 00:10:03.260
&gt;&gt; Herve Boutry: Yeah,
there is a very big change

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:08.600
because it's not only the music
directors it's also the world

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:10.020
which has changed.

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:14.410
And the music world is
changing, I mean all the time.

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:23.830
And I think the 10 last years it
has been very obviously opening up.

00:10:23.830 --> 00:10:28.060
The music world is
going from a more --

00:10:28.060 --> 00:10:38.790
from a quite segmented attitude in
the past where modern institution

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:42.680
of people were modernists.

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:50.500
And now you have all classical
or [inaudible] to be authentic.

00:10:50.500 --> 00:10:56.750
And now you have a different trend
which is to try and go to the root,

00:10:56.750 --> 00:11:00.940
to the essence of the
music and to try

00:11:00.940 --> 00:11:06.000
and find not a common denominator,
but a stronger experience,

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:11.880
particularly in this time where
internet where one can imagine

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:18.030
that 15 or 20 years ago we didn't
have internet as we have it now.

00:11:18.030 --> 00:11:24.090
And it's absolutely
obvious with young composers

00:11:24.090 --> 00:11:27.780
that they are writing in the
world with internet differently

00:11:27.780 --> 00:11:30.500
than they were writing before.

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:36.860
The relationship with
the others has changed

00:11:36.860 --> 00:11:41.770
and that's also explaining
the evolution of the Ensemble,

00:11:41.770 --> 00:11:48.870
the Ensemble is an institution, a
contemporary institution and has

00:11:48.870 --> 00:11:56.770
to move forward in this
environment and tries to do it

00:11:56.770 --> 00:11:59.100
on the most pertinent way.

00:12:00.390 --> 00:12:02.940
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Do you feel
a weight on your shoulders

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:07.100
as a successor of Boulez
in your role?

00:12:07.100 --> 00:12:09.900
&gt;&gt; Matthias Pintscher: I
would rather, honestly I hope

00:12:09.900 --> 00:12:12.270
that does sound arrogant because
I really don't mean it that way.

00:12:12.270 --> 00:12:17.000 position:56%
But I almost feel more encouragement
than weight because everything

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:20.800
that Boulez cared about is the
passing on and the sharing.

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:24.180
He might be even the only one

00:12:24.180 --> 00:12:30.410
who has been almost aggressively
curious about what we do.

00:12:30.410 --> 00:12:36.830
And all these encounters I
had with him and everything

00:12:36.830 --> 00:12:42.280 position:56%
that built our friendship and our
connection is based on his curiosity

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:47.850
of hearing me what I was starting
with, what I wanted to know.

00:12:47.850 --> 00:12:50.220
And every time that goes years back

00:12:50.220 --> 00:12:55.140
when I was conducting a major
new work of the repertoire

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:59.790
of the 20th century, I'm
talking about [inaudible].

00:12:59.790 --> 00:13:04.180
He was so generous to share his
time with me and I most went

00:13:04.180 --> 00:13:09.380
to Baden-Baden and we sat there
on his [inaudible] couch for hours

00:13:09.380 --> 00:13:12.740
and hours and hours and shared.

00:13:12.740 --> 00:13:21.050
So I rather feel a tremendous
enlightenment than the weight.

00:13:21.050 --> 00:13:28.430
But of course and but he would be
really, really he is very excited

00:13:28.430 --> 00:13:31.390
to see that we're moving things
forward whatever that means.

00:13:31.390 --> 00:13:34.860
Because the movement itself of
going forward and I'm not talking

00:13:34.860 --> 00:13:39.190
of avant-garde, but just the
keeping, that fact the condition

00:13:39.190 --> 00:13:43.110
of keeping walking
is way more important

00:13:43.110 --> 00:13:47.230
than the sensation of arrival.

00:13:47.230 --> 00:13:50.700
Fulfillment puts everything
in question,

00:13:50.700 --> 00:13:53.760
we always go back to the score.

00:13:53.760 --> 00:13:57.710
And, you know, we're an institution
that is living on the basis

00:13:57.710 --> 00:14:00.100
of all the scores that
have been conceived

00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:02.370
and that have been
purchased right now

00:14:02.370 --> 00:14:04.800
and hopefully will be
written in the future.

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:09.740
This is Boulez, Boulez is look at
the score and take it from there.

00:14:09.740 --> 00:14:13.210
And it's not about me and how I
define that [inaudible] because I

00:14:13.210 --> 00:14:17.540
like it that way or no, it
needs to come out of the score.

00:14:17.540 --> 00:14:22.060
And I'd rather take that as a
tremendous potential of inspiration

00:14:22.060 --> 00:14:25.570
than feeling intimidated and I
hope you understand it [inaudible].

00:14:25.570 --> 00:14:28.020
&gt;&gt; Nicholas Brown: Oh yeah, I
think it's wonderful to hear

00:14:28.020 --> 00:14:33.280
that perspective because
at least people that come

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:36.460
up through the US system and
knowing whatever happened

00:14:36.460 --> 00:14:41.340
with in [inaudible] there's just
this aura around him that from

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:44.620 position:56%
when you actually hear from someone
who knows him and interacts with him

00:14:44.620 --> 00:14:50.260
on a very personal level that
sort of being isn't the reality.

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:53.500
So it's such a treat for
us to have you all here

00:14:53.500 --> 00:14:57.400
to give us the real honest
perspective on his legacy.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:02.670 position:56%
Tell us a bit about your recent
performance of [inaudible] in Paris.

00:15:02.670 --> 00:15:03.970
&gt;&gt; Matthias Pintscher:

00:15:03.970 --> 00:15:10.610
Well [inaudible] is some people
consider it as his opus maximum and

00:15:10.610 --> 00:15:16.420
but he wrote many opus
maxima or maximi,

00:15:16.420 --> 00:15:26.320
opi maximi is that the Latin
plural [inaudible] said that.

00:15:26.320 --> 00:15:29.420
But [inaudible] culminates
in an ingenious way

00:15:29.420 --> 00:15:35.620
of really combining the electronics
and real sound to a level

00:15:35.620 --> 00:15:38.240
that is maybe really unbeaten.

00:15:38.240 --> 00:15:45.200
It's a work that is driven
by a great sense for color

00:15:45.200 --> 00:15:47.260
and virtuosity, which
are two aspects

00:15:47.260 --> 00:15:54.720
that very much define partly
what we consider as French.

00:15:54.720 --> 00:16:00.420 position:56%
But underneath it there's is a
great level and depth of expression.

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:08.830
And I always like it very much
to compare Boulez to Ravel

00:16:08.830 --> 00:16:12.310
because they are composed of their
personalities that were very,

00:16:12.310 --> 00:16:15.960
very conscious on how
to set up a composition,

00:16:15.960 --> 00:16:18.300
but then also to allow it to fly

00:16:18.300 --> 00:16:22.720
and enhance the richness
that is living inside.

00:16:22.720 --> 00:16:24.460
Very controlled from the outside,

00:16:24.460 --> 00:16:29.410
but equally strong
emotionally on the inside.

00:16:29.410 --> 00:16:35.300
And so in that aspect for me as
a colleague if I may call myself

00:16:35.300 --> 00:16:41.110
so it is fantastic to sit
down and be a scholar and read

00:16:41.110 --> 00:16:43.580
and analyze those scores,
but at the same time

00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:46.820
when I can just abandon all
that and perform the music

00:16:46.820 --> 00:16:50.640
from the performer's angle is
equally as strong and there's not

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:55.380
that much repertoire that is
being written nor has been written

00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:58.360
recently that has both
those qualities

00:16:58.360 --> 00:17:02.030
which are extremely
appealing to me personally.

00:17:03.080 --> 00:17:05.350
&gt;&gt; Herve Boutry: I want
to add something which is

00:17:05.350 --> 00:17:11.180
that Pierre Boulez is also a
personality who has a global vision

00:17:11.180 --> 00:17:19.830
of his artistry and for him art is
not only writing music on a paper,

00:17:19.830 --> 00:17:26.870
it's also conducting, it's
also working with musicians,

00:17:26.870 --> 00:17:30.730
but it's also working
with architects,

00:17:30.730 --> 00:17:36.940
with people from all
sorts of disciplines.

00:17:36.940 --> 00:17:41.040
And there is a very
strong [inaudible],

00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:44.940 position:56%
which affects me very strongly of
course because it's the architecture

00:17:44.940 --> 00:17:48.620
of the whole is a set of work
which has to be performed

00:17:48.620 --> 00:17:53.740
with the ensemble in the middle and
the soloist around the audience.

00:17:53.740 --> 00:17:57.700
And the electronics
transforms the sound

00:17:57.700 --> 00:18:04.650
and the electronic is projected in
addition to the acoustic sounds.

00:18:04.650 --> 00:18:11.150
And it is -- it was very obvious
this year we performed it three

00:18:11.150 --> 00:18:20.320
times in very different places
and I know that it is a challenge

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:28.350
which Pierre considered
as part of his work.

00:18:28.350 --> 00:18:32.010
This challenge to find
the best conditions

