00:29:42.850 --> 00:29:47.890
I believe your answer to that first
question pertaining more to the way

00:29:47.890 --> 00:29:50.600
that people have their
own way of understanding.

00:29:50.600 --> 00:29:55.630
But I got the impression from
the avant-garde of the 60's

00:29:55.630 --> 00:30:00.050
that in many cases composers
were inventing their own language

00:30:00.050 --> 00:30:02.330
sometimes with each composition,

00:30:02.330 --> 00:30:09.760
whereas in other cases listeners
might want to look for illusions

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:12.940
or understanding based upon
all of musical history.

00:30:12.940 --> 00:30:14.950
So any comments on that?

00:30:14.950 --> 00:30:20.880
&gt;&gt; Matthias Pintscher: Well let's
maybe take this back a couple years

00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:24.750 position:56%
more and look at what happened after
the Second World War and I'm talking

00:30:24.750 --> 00:30:30.380
about what has been written and
composed in Europe after the war.

00:30:30.380 --> 00:30:37.260
And it seems like there was a
certain need for some objectivity

00:30:37.260 --> 00:30:41.900
in what was composed because
everything had fallen apart

00:30:41.900 --> 00:30:46.910
and the people were so speechless
and they didn't have the courage

00:30:46.910 --> 00:30:51.750 position:56%
or were not feeling strong enough to
just continue to be just subjective

00:30:51.750 --> 00:30:54.240
and they needed to
objectify themselves.

00:30:54.240 --> 00:30:57.560
And that's why that music
that was written in the 50's

00:30:57.560 --> 00:31:04.230 position:56%
and even the 60's so extremely
organized because maybe the majority

00:31:04.230 --> 00:31:06.670
of the composers in Europe felt
like they needed to be able

00:31:06.670 --> 00:31:09.250
to argument why they
put that F sharp here

00:31:09.250 --> 00:31:13.150
and why they don't use the double
bases in the second movement.

00:31:13.150 --> 00:31:17.540
And then all these decisions
had some argumentation handy

00:31:17.540 --> 00:31:18.960
and ready to go.

00:31:18.960 --> 00:31:27.510 position:56%
And then with growing courage people
again all re-immersed themselves

00:31:27.510 --> 00:31:32.010
in the pleasure of living
in diversity and then all

00:31:32.010 --> 00:31:36.310
of a sudden even like the major
works of the 70's allowed again

00:31:36.310 --> 00:31:45.630
that quality of physicality, color
and yes emotion to be re-included.

00:31:45.630 --> 00:31:52.590
And that's why I always
plead my case to the listener

00:31:52.590 --> 00:31:57.940
to please not be so
strung up on the fact

00:31:57.940 --> 00:32:00.550
that we think we can
understand a piece of art

00:32:00.550 --> 00:32:03.310
because that's what happens
to us when we go to school.

00:32:03.310 --> 00:32:06.850
And when I was being taught how

00:32:06.850 --> 00:32:11.010
to understand the second Viennese
school and in particular a work

00:32:11.010 --> 00:32:15.170
by Anton Webern where, you know,
the melody is being played that way

00:32:15.170 --> 00:32:18.550
and then is being played
backwards and then it's mirrored

00:32:18.550 --> 00:32:21.840
and you just mark this all with
differently colored crayons

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:24.330
and [inaudible] and you think
you understand the piece.

00:32:24.330 --> 00:32:25.630
That's what happened to me.

00:32:25.630 --> 00:32:30.830
But no one was talking to us about
why that no flute with all that air

00:32:30.830 --> 00:32:35.980
in the sound had this
erratic quality.

00:32:35.980 --> 00:32:41.150 position:56%
