that D flat in opus 10 why

00:32:41.150 --> 00:32:43.940
that note doesn't really --

00:32:43.940 --> 00:32:46.720
the physically the
instrument doesn't allow

00:32:46.720 --> 00:32:51.600 position:56%
that note is not any more brilliant,
but it contains so much emotion.

00:32:51.600 --> 00:32:53.940
And I wish and that's what
I'm doing with my students

00:32:53.940 --> 00:32:59.900
at Julliard we do a completely
new way of analyzing a work,

00:32:59.900 --> 00:33:02.420
we doing an erratic analysis,

00:33:02.420 --> 00:33:05.370
no more crayons we just
talk about what we hear.

00:33:05.370 --> 00:33:09.570
And I so wish that the listener
could just do exactly the same.

00:33:09.570 --> 00:33:13.510
Leave your crayons at home and
no, I'm serious because we are

00:33:13.510 --> 00:33:19.070
so determined by thinking analogies
and then feeling accomplished

00:33:19.070 --> 00:33:21.610
when we understand a piece of art.

00:33:21.610 --> 00:33:25.040
